But it was not until August 4th, after many scenes of riot and bloodshed‚—for the partizans of-Cicero had begun to use violence to meet the violence of Clodius,—that the bill for Cicero’s recall was passed in the assembly of the people. Cicero reached Rome September 4th. His homeward journey had been one continual ovation. All Italy put on gala attire to wel- come the returning exile. When he reached Rome the “ entire population '' flocked to the gates to greet him. His ride through the streets to the Capitol was a triumphal procession which the mightiest imperator might have envied him. “ This day,'' he writeS, “ was to me like immortality.'’

Cicero had been absent about a year and a half. He re· turned amidst most flattering evidences of popularity. He took at'once his old place in the senate,‘delivering there and in the Forum verybelaborate speeches of thanks for his recall.
